Project: Stroke Prediction Model¶

Purpose¶

The purpose of this project is to create a stroke prediction machine learning model to predict the likelihood that a person will experience a stroke based on their health and their lifestyle.

This enables early intervention, preventive care, and better resource allocation in healthcare.

The main goals are:

  • Risk Assessment - Identify individuals at high risk of stroke before symptoms occur
  • Action - Help doctors recommend lifestyle changes, medication, or monitoring to reduce stroke risk.
  • Early Diagnosis - Assist general practitioners and screening programs in prioritizing patients
  • Personalized Care - Provide patient-specific insights based on predictive features (e.g., glucose levels, age).
  • Cost reduction - Lower long-term healthcare costs by preventing severe complications through early detection.

ROI¶

The return of investment meant to be achieved is

  • Reduced Hospitalizations - Early detection reduces emergency admissions, ICU stays, and long-term care costs.
  • Lower Treatment Costs - Preventive treatment is cheaper than managing stroke aftermath (e.g., rehab, surgery).
  • Faster Response Time - High-risk patients are flagged earlier, leading to faster diagnosis and fewer complications.
  • Decreased Readmission Rates - Monitoring and follow-up for high-risk patients improves outcomes and reduces return visits.
  • Optimized Resource Allocation - Healthcare systems can focus on the most vulnerable patients, improving efficiency.

Data Preprocessing¶

Having seen BMI variable with null values I would like to check how many features contains nulls and how many per each of them.

Also I would like to check the data type and some statistics overview

I can see that the variable bmi has many missing values. I need to decide if drop the rows with missing values or if interpolate using the mean

In regard to the statistical part, I can see that:

  • The age standard deviation of ~ 22.6 suggest a good variability of the population selected for this study. In fact the min age is 0.08 and the max is 82 years old
  • Hypertension and hearth desease is not often remarked in this selected population
  • Avg glucose level ranges indicate the presence of both normal and diabetic individuals
  • BMI mean is ~28.9 (overweight category). Max value of 97.6 is suspiciously high. This is needed to be handled.
  • stroke (our target variable) is "fortunately" only 4.87 % of the cases.

The stroke rarity suggest a strong class imbalance, which justifies using SMOTE or similar techniques (that we will see later in this project, during the modelling phase)

Remark¶

Some research on internet showed that for clinical guidelines the BMI stops between 40 and 50.

However since in reality it is possible to find some patient with extreme high BMI but usually no more than 60 I would remove the lines with BMI more than 60 to be sure to not pollute the all dataset.

In fact these cases are possible but so rare than in most of the cases they are data entry errors.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In this chapter I will examine and understand the dataset before building a model.

This helps to detect patterns, identify anomalies, and generate insights to guide preprocessing and for modeling decisions.

Correlation Analysis¶

None of the variables show particularly strong correlations with stroke

The strongest correlations with stroke are:

  • Age: 0.25 (weak positive)
  • Heart_disease: 0.13 (very weak positive)
  • Hypertension: 0.13 (very weak positive)
  • Avg_glucose_level: 0.13 (very weak positive)
Deduction:¶

The relatively weak correlations suggest that no single variable is a strong predictor of stroke on its own.

Age appears to be the most correlated feature, indicating that stroke risk increases somewhat with age.

Health factors (heart_disease, hypertension, glucose level) show slight positive associations with stroke.

Therefore it is likely needed to use multiple features together to build an effective predictive model.

Point of attention on the smoker patients:¶

With surprise, smoking does not appear to have a strong correlation with stroke in this dataset. This might be because strokes are relatively rare among younger individuals, even those who smoke

Interestingly, there is a very weak correlation with former smokers, which could be explained by the fact that people often quit smoking as they age—possibly due to emerging health concerns. This further reinforces the observation that age is the most strongly correlated factor with stroke.

On the other hand, individuals who have never smoked show the lowest incidence of stroke, suggesting a protective effect. This could imply that smoking may cause long-term damage to blood circulation in the brain, which is not fully reversible even after quitting.

Analysis of numerical variables¶

Age vs. Stroke:¶

As already mentioned above the age is the most incisive risk factor.

People who experienced strokes tend to be significantly older than those who didn't.

In fact the median age for stroke patients is 71 years old versus the no-stroke that is 43.

This supports the correlation value of 0.25 of above correlation matrix, confirming age is a relevant predictor

Average Glucose Level vs. Stroke:¶

People with strokes tend to have higher average glucose levels. The median glucose level appears slightly higher in the stroke group.

The stroke group shows wider variability in glucose levels. Some extreme high values appear in the non-stroke group (outliers).

This relationship appears stronger in the visualization than the 0.13 correlation suggested.

There is visible separation between the two groups' glucose distributions, particularly in their upper quartiles.

However due to weak correlation that we saw above, as a stroke predictor, avg_glucose_level provides some signal, but it's not a strong predictor on its own.

The boxplot that comes after, shows that while higher glucose tends to be associated with stroke, many people with high glucose don't have strokes, and some people with normal glucose do have strokes.

BMI vs. Stroke:¶

Surprisingly, BMI distributions look very similar between stroke and non-stroke groups.

Median BMI values are nearly identical between the two groups, that is around 28

The non-stroke group has more outliers with very high BMI values

This suggests BMI alone is a poor predictor of stroke

# Create age groups

df_age_group['age_group'] = pd.cut(df_age_group['age'], bins=[0, 30, 45, 60, 100], labels=['<30', '30-45', '45-60', '60+'])

smoking_columns = [col for col in df_age_group.columns if col.startswith('smoking_status_')]


# For each smoking status, check stroke rate by age group
for smoking_col in smoking_columns:
    status_name = smoking_col.replace('smoking_status_', '')
    print(f"\nStroke rate (%) for {status_name} by age group:")
    
    # Filter for only people with this smoking status
    subset = df_age_group[df_age_group[smoking_col] == True]
    
    # Calculate and print stroke rate by age group
    stroke_by_age = subset.groupby('age_group', observed=True)['stroke'].mean() * 100
    print(stroke_by_age)
    
    # Visualize
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    stroke_by_age.plot(kind='bar', color='teal')

    plt.ylabel('Stroke Rate (%)')
    plt.xlabel('Age Group')
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Prepare the dataset¶

After all the EDA perfrmed above I can start to prepare my dataset to be used for modelling.

As said above, the distribution of my dataset is clearly imbalanced (also shown in below bar chart and stroke rate), with far fewer stroke cases (stroke == 1) than non-stroke cases (stroke == 0).

This can bias my machine learning model toward predicting the majority class.

This will be treated during the modelling phase.

Feature importance¶

In a previous version on my project I decided to drop some features for which the correlation with stroke was appearing not linked. But then I saw that the model was not performing much better so I decided to keep all features. Because correlation shouldn't be the only reason to drop a feature—especially in classification problems since:

  • Some features may not show a strong linear correlation with the target but still hold nonlinear or interaction effects.
  • Some features may be important for fairness or interpretability, like gender or residence type, depending on the context.

Deal with imbalanced dataset¶

There are two options that I can use to balance my dataset:

  • Option 1: Upsampling minority class (resample)
  • Option 2: SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique)
  • Option 3: using balanced functionality that are available for some models.

I will use the 2nd and 3rd option because the resample technique is simpler but may overfit due to duplicate rows.

NB: The SMOTE technique will produce syntetic data. To use it all features must be numerical, and this was already done during the encoding phase.

In [22]:
# I do the train / test split before SMOTE, since the SMOTE need to be done only to training set only to avoid data leakage and overfitting
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=25)

# SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique)
smote = SMOTE(random_state=25)
X_train_smo, y_train_smo = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

Train and Evaluate on Original unbalanced Data¶

The RandomForestClassifier trained on the original (unbalanced) data almost never predicted any strokes during cross-validation.

That means:

  • Precision and recall for stroke both became zero (or almost zero)
  • Therefore F1 score also dropped to zero (or almost zero)

The classifier got overwhelmed by the dominant class (non-stroke) and defaults to predicting almost everything as non-stroke.

Even if the accuracy is 95% (very high) the recall and precision for the stroke case is zero, this means it predicted zero strokes.

The conclusion on this dataset is that it is not safe to be used the way it is (unbalanced).

Let's see the results using balancing techniques.

I will first create the model and cross-validate it and then retrain the model with the full train dataset for all the models I will use

Train a Model on the Resampled Data¶

I will now train the model using balanced data.

SMOTE¶

The first technique is the SMOTE.

The cross validation shows very consistent performance across all 5 cv folds. The average F1 score of 0.968 confirms that the model generalizes well across different subsets of the data and is particularlyseems effective at identifying both stroke and non-stroke cases.

However the performance on the actual test set is poor for the positive (stroke) class. It completely fails to generalize to stroke cases. The model may have overfitted to the synthetic minority samples.

I will not proceed with this model

Balanced Random Forest¶

In cv phase the low F1 scores (especially below 0.30) indicate that the model struggles to effectively identify the minority class (stroke cases), even with this model.

However, using the full train data there is a decent number of correctly identified stroke cases (TP = 33), but a high number of false positives (193), which may cause over-alerting.

This model is already better than the SMOTE one.

In real life it's better to create an over-alert than a under-alert.

In [28]:
# This model does not need to use SMOTE data because it will balance the data automatically
brf_cv = BalancedRandomForestClassifier(random_state=25, n_estimators=300)

# Cross-validate on the training set (before fitting to all training data)

Threshold tuning to increase sensitivity to the minority class¶

Now, using the best parameters I will fine tune the best threshold.

With this fine tuning we can see that lowering the threshold the recall is increasing so we can catch more stroke cases, while the precisions will drop because a lot of non-stroke cases get misclassified.

With this model I would use a threshold of 0.5 (default) or 0.4, but not less than this because with lesser value the model will predict too much false positive stroke cases.

In [31]:
# Train the model using bets parameters
brf = BalancedRandomForestClassifier(
    random_state=25,
    n_estimators=300,
    min_samples_split=2,
    min_samples_leaf=1,
    max_depth=20)
brf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get predicted probabilities for stroke cases
y_probs = brf.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Define the thresholds to test
thresholds = [0.5, 0.4, 0.3, 0.2]

# Evaluate model at each threshold
for threshold in thresholds:
    y_pred_thresh = (y_probs >= threshold).astype(int)

    print(f"\n=== Threshold: {threshold} ===")
    print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_thresh))
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_thresh, digits=3))

XG Boost¶

I will use XG Boost because the Gradient Boosting does not perform well with unbalanced data.

Only 6 out of 50 stroke cases were correctly identified. The model is biased toward the majority class (non-stroke), despite the scale_pos_weight.

This model is not convincing.

In [35]:
# Calculate scale_pos_weight = (number of negative samples / number of positive samples)
neg, pos = (y_train == 0).sum(), (y_train == 1).sum()
scale = neg / pos
print(f"scale_pos_weight: {scale:.2f}")

# Create pipeline
xgb_pip = make_pipeline(
    StandardScaler(),  # optional
    XGBClassifier(n_estimators=100,
                  scale_pos_weight=scale,
                  use_label_encoder=False,
                  eval_metric='logloss',
                  random_state=25)
)

# Train

Conclusion¶

My conclusion is that I would recommend to use the Logistic regression model.

Even though Balanced Random Forest has slightly better AUC, the Logistic Regression model has the highest recall for the minority class (stroke) with a better precision (less false positive to stroke). With this I mean that to have a similar level of recall using the Balanced RF it si necessary to use a threshold of 0.4, but the precision will be worse than the Logistic Regression model.

I think this is crucial in a medical diagnosis context. Missing a real stroke case (false negative) is much worse than predicting a stroke that isn’t there (false positive).

Moreover, logistic regression is:

  • Easier to interpret
  • Faster to train
  • More transparent in medical applications
